01:05:36.117 --> 01:05:38.158
IAIN STEWART: No, you have
to look at loops, too.

01:05:38.158 --> 01:05:39.870
So, yeah, there can
be cancellations

01:05:39.870 --> 01:05:41.820
between real and virtual graphs.

01:05:41.820 --> 01:05:44.070
And there actually can
be such cancellations

01:05:44.070 --> 01:05:46.680
separately for ultra soft
gluons and for collinear gluons.

01:05:46.680 --> 01:05:48.930
So we'll talk about what
you're talking about a little

01:05:48.930 --> 01:05:50.440
later on.

01:05:50.440 --> 01:05:52.770
But there is an important
point that I'll emphasize

01:05:52.770 --> 01:05:54.180
since you ask the question.

01:05:54.180 --> 01:05:56.310
If you ask about
the divergences,

01:05:56.310 --> 01:06:00.240
the infrared divergences
of an ultra soft gluon, so

01:06:00.240 --> 01:06:02.790
the ultra soft gluon, if we go
back to sort of where it was

01:06:02.790 --> 01:06:05.770
living, it was littered here.

01:06:05.770 --> 01:06:08.440
Collinear gluon was living here.

01:06:08.440 --> 01:06:10.410
And if you ask
about divergences,

01:06:10.410 --> 01:06:11.910
what the divergences
are coming from

01:06:11.910 --> 01:06:15.390
are momenta going to 0 or
momentum going collinear.

01:06:15.390 --> 01:06:18.240
And this guy here that
lives kind of here

01:06:18.240 --> 01:06:22.980
can go both collinear,
and it can go soft.

01:06:22.980 --> 01:06:25.320
So the names collinear
and soft, which

01:06:25.320 --> 01:06:28.200
correspond to the names
collinear and soft divergences,

01:06:28.200 --> 01:06:30.610
are not a one-to-one
correspondence.

01:06:30.610 --> 01:06:34.800
An ultra soft
particle can actually

01:06:34.800 --> 01:06:38.940
have both collinear
and soft divergences.

01:06:38.940 --> 01:06:40.770
The collinear particle
can also actually

01:06:40.770 --> 01:06:43.500
have both types of divergences.

01:06:43.500 --> 01:06:45.450
And so the names are
associated to where

01:06:45.450 --> 01:06:48.030
they live in momentum space,
not the type of divergences

01:06:48.030 --> 01:06:49.140
that they're encoding.

01:06:49.140 --> 01:06:51.630
If I wanted to do something
along the lines of setting up

01:06:51.630 --> 01:06:55.685
the field theory to just exactly
correspond to the divergences,

01:06:55.685 --> 01:06:57.060
well, first of
all, no one's ever

01:06:57.060 --> 01:06:58.750
figured out how to do that.

01:06:58.750 --> 01:07:00.292
But you could imagine
how it would be

01:07:00.292 --> 01:07:01.542
different than what I'm doing.

01:07:01.542 --> 01:07:03.420
Because if I wanted to
do that, then somehow

01:07:03.420 --> 01:07:06.570
my collinear field would sort of
be sort of sensitive to angles.

01:07:06.570 --> 01:07:08.580
It should be like
an angular variable

01:07:08.580 --> 01:07:11.940
because the divergences are
coming from angles going to 0.

01:07:11.940 --> 01:07:13.630
And it's not an
angular variable.

01:07:13.630 --> 01:07:15.402
It's just a regular field.

01:07:15.402 --> 01:07:16.860
So setting things
up in this way is

01:07:16.860 --> 01:07:19.590
kind of how we usually think
of an effective field theory.

01:07:19.590 --> 01:07:22.140
We're just talking about
momenta small or big.

01:07:22.140 --> 01:07:24.870
And that's what we're doing,
but it comes in the sense

01:07:24.870 --> 01:07:27.720
that you don't have a
direct correspondence

01:07:27.720 --> 01:07:31.520
with the divergences.

01:07:31.520 --> 01:07:35.213
AUDIENCE: So you have more
divergences [INAUDIBLE]??

01:07:35.213 --> 01:07:36.630
IAIN STEWART: The
way of saying it

01:07:36.630 --> 01:07:41.010
is that you have more
divergences in a way,

01:07:41.010 --> 01:07:43.460
but they're the
same divergences--

01:07:43.460 --> 01:07:44.760
yeah.

01:07:44.760 --> 01:07:45.960
Yeah.

01:07:45.960 --> 01:07:48.480
So you don't have
more divergences,

01:07:48.480 --> 01:07:52.020
but really what's happening is--

01:07:52.020 --> 01:07:56.220
so if you look at
this kind of picture,

01:07:56.220 --> 01:07:58.200
if you look at the kind
of infrared divergences

01:07:58.200 --> 01:08:01.740
that you could have,
so let's regulate them

01:08:01.740 --> 01:08:03.660
with an off-shellness.

01:08:03.660 --> 01:08:05.160
You could have
infrared divergences

01:08:05.160 --> 01:08:07.530
that would be like that.

01:08:07.530 --> 01:08:10.830
But when you do some
diagrams, there's

01:08:10.830 --> 01:08:16.620
kind of infrared divergences
that could look like this, OK?

01:08:16.620 --> 01:08:19.350
I'm just telling you something
that you have to trust me.

01:08:19.350 --> 01:08:22.140
And this is coming from
an ultra soft scale.

01:08:22.140 --> 01:08:25.380
P squared over P minus,
that's this hyperbola.

01:08:25.380 --> 01:08:27.720
That's the scale
of this hyperbola.

01:08:27.720 --> 01:08:30.630
And the P squared here is
the scale of this hyperbola.

01:08:30.630 --> 01:08:33.540
What the effective theory does
is, any ultra soft diagram,

01:08:33.540 --> 01:08:35.819
that'll give all these logs.

01:08:35.819 --> 01:08:40.560
Any collinear diagram
will give all these logs.

01:08:40.560 --> 01:08:42.930
You could say, well, P
minus is a hard scale.

01:08:42.930 --> 01:08:46.696
So really the only the IR
divergences are just P squared,

01:08:46.696 --> 01:08:48.779
but the effective theory
is kind of dividing it up

01:08:48.779 --> 01:08:50.069
into these two types of logs.

